<a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo/journal/" title="Sunday September 17, 2023 @09:53AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64696134"><p><div class="quote"><p>The same could be said when crowdstrike bricked linux boxes</p></div><p>Crowdstrike did not <em>brick</em> anything. The definition of bricking is rendering a device <em>unresponsive</em> to the point that it takes heroic measures to resurrect it, such as reprogramming the firmware. The fix for Crowdstrike's massive failure was relatively simple and did not require any such heroics. They did, however, render the Windows systems unable to boot.</p><p> <strong>Crowdstrike did not do the same to Linux systems</strong>. The Linux systems suffering from a <em>similar</em> failure from Crowdstrike were experiencing kernel panics <em>after running for several minutes</em>. This means that it was possible to get into them and fix them <em>remotely</em>, which means they were even <em>less</em> like being bricked than the Windows systems Crowdstrike <em>also</em> didn't "brick".</p><p>Since you have no understanding of the issues involved, or the meanings of words which are very well established in the technical community, it can be concluded that you having nothing of value to add to this conversation &mdash; and it's easy to see why you were too cowardly to not click the anonymous posting box.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64696134">
