		on Sunday August 11, 2024 @06:03AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23418236&amp;cid=64696098">#64696098</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64696098"><p>CrowdStrike didn't have process in which before they released any updates to production, they would just release them to a actual canary environment to make sure it didn't catch all the machines on fire. Which you need to do when you have kernel code.</p><p>Not to mention that the driver seems to be poorly written with a ton of sanity checks missing.</p><p>Finally, Microsoft did propose an API to allow security vendors what they needed in user space. The EU killed it as anti-competitive because MS wouldn't also have to use it, but continue to use kernel drivers, completely ignoring that user-mode code is way easier to write, making it easier for new and smaller business to compete and nothing MS did would prevent you from using kernel drivers if you wanted to.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64696098">
